	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yeah, if you read "Game Over" or "The Ultimate History of Video Games" they go into greater detail about this period, and it was insane what Nintendo had to do just to get the NES in NYC stores.  Retailers had been so badly stung by the crash of '83 that Nintendo practically had to beg them for a chance.  Some of NOA's early employees (including then-president Minoru Arakawa) even had to set up and stock the displays in toy stores themselves.  Can you imagine that?
<br />
<br />Of course, the NES picked up steam in New York and then nationwide, and needless to say it wasn't long before Nintendo was finished begging.  Soon everyone else was begging them.

		

		</td>
